Using age with your yubikey is not post quantum proof yet. Unfortunatle only age keys generated manualy are quantum proof. its also not possible to copy a age-key into your yubikey its only possible to have your yubikey generate a age key.
So if you are really serious about PQ-proof encryption your yubikey is not the tool you want to use. 


You need a extra tool for this function
install it with 
```bash
sudo apt install pcscd
sudo systemctl enable --now pcscd
```

Via cargo you need to install age-plugin-yubikey if you dont have cargo install this first with 
```bash
cargo install age-plugin-yubikey
```


When you are going to use age-encryption, you will need to configure a few things before you get started. It is extremely important to always first change your managemnt-key at the piv options.

The factory default management key from every yubikey is 010203040506070801020304050607080102030405060708 and you really need to change this!

There are two ways of generating a managemnt-key with or without  the --portect

With the protect option you let the yubikey generate it based on your pin
```bash
ykman piv access change-management-key --generate --protect
```

without the protect option the yubikeu  generates the key and you store it somewhere offline (on a usb or print it or create a qrcode from it)
```bash
ykman piv access change-management-key --generate
```
In my case it store the managemnt-key offline so i just run 
```bash 
ykman piv access change-management-key -a TDES --protect
```

Now you have to change the pin and puk code by

Change PIN with (default pin is 123456)
```bash
ykman piv access change-pin
```

Change PUK with (default puk is 12345678)
```bash
ykman piv access change-puk
```
Now you took all the masurements to generate your age Identityfile (or private key) with your Yubikey.
Unfortunatly there is no way you can copy a existing Age-identity file to your yubikey. but you can encrypt files with multipble keys, so you can create backups. 

Run the age-plugin-yubikey and follow the menu.
```bash
age-plugin-yubikey
```
a file is generate thats  age-yubikey-identity-*.txt the line that starts with Recipient: is yout public key. 

an other way of finding your public key is to print public key with the  age-plugin-yubikey --list command, the last line is your public key, its a long string
``bash
age-plugin-yubikey --list
```

You can encrypt files with multiple age identities, so just add multiple recipients while you encrpy a file. for example i have 2 yubikeys and one offline key




